{
  "doc_id": "7436",
  "text": "The exact pathophysiological mechanisms of AESD or AED remain unknown [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Further, discrimination between AESD and prolonged febrile seizure in the early phase is difficult as there are no useful biomarkers [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . We experienced a case of a girl with an old brain abscess in the right frontal lobe who developed secondary generalized SE twice (3 and 4 years of age). Although she made a full recovery at the first SE episode, she developed AED following the second SE with a monophasic clinical course. Herein, we compare the DWI and ASL findings on day 4 after the onset of each SE, and discuss the possible pathophysiological mechanisms of AED with respect to metabolic and circulatory changes detected on ASL and DWI.",
